The '''Organization of Angolan Women''', established in 1962,<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EFI7tr9XK6EC&pg=PA54&dq=%22Organization+of+Angolan+Women%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjv8PGO4_TaAhVDPN8KHYwWC9MQ6AEIMjAC#v=onepage&q=%22Organization%20of%20Angolan%20Women%22&f=false|title=The Oxford Encyclopedia of Women in World History|last=Smith|first=Bonnie G.|date=2008|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=|isbn=9780195148909|location=|pages=54|language=en}}</ref> was originally founded to rally support for the new political party known as the [[MPLA]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://africanactivist.msu.edu/document_metadata.php?objectid=32-130-47C|title=Liberation in Southern Africa: The Organization of Angolan Women|last=|first=|date=|website=African Activist Archive (Michigan State University)|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2018-05-07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=X95R043HBJwC&pg=PA452&dq=%22Organization+of+Angolan+Women%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjv8PGO4_TaAhVDPN8KHYwWC9MQ6AEILTAB#v=onepage&q=%22Organization%20of%20Angolan%20Women%22&f=false|title=Women and Revolution in Africa, Asia, and the New World|last=Tétreault|first=Mary Ann|date=1994|publisher=Univ of South Carolina Press|year=|isbn=9781570030161|location=|pages=95, 97-100|language=en}}</ref> Once [[Angola]] was officially independent of Portugal in 1975 following the [[Angolan War of Independence]], the Organization of Angolan Women provided the best opportunity for female activism in local government. Total involvement faltered in the 1980s, citing that rural violence and regional destabilization disheartened many of the rural members. However, it was also during the 1980s that Angola passed the first [[anti-discrimination law]]s and established strict [[literacy]] laws to support uneducated women.<ref>Popular Movement for the Liberation of Angola-Workers' Party (Movimento Popular de Libertação de Angola-Partido de Trabalho). Angola: Trabalho e luta. Paris: Réalisation (Edições DIP), 1985.</ref>

